# Slice scope fidelity (Seismo 0.5)

The `.cursor/rules/` guardrails enforce **architecture**. They do not enforce **scope**. That has to come from here.

## The failure mode this rule exists to prevent

Slice 1 (the read-only dashboard) was shipped with four 0.4 UI affordances silently removed: search box, tag filter pills, favourites view toggle, nav drawer. The commit message labelled them "deliberately out of scope — they come back in later slices" without naming which slice, without updating `docs/consolidation-plan.md`, and without asking. In six weeks nobody reading the repo would find them — they'd live only in a git commit message.

This is a soft failure: every individual step is defensible ("definition of done only mentioned the cards"), but the cumulative effect is scope erosion. If Slice 1 drops four UI pieces unasked, Slice 2 can drop "Lex settings tab" by the same logic, Slice 3 can drop the Leg cron pipeline because "cron catches up later", and we end up shipping a 0.5 that is architecturally cleaner than 0.4 but functionally diminished — and we never noticed because each step was locally reasonable.

## The hard rule

**Before collapsing any feature present in 0.4 out of a slice's delivered scope, the agent must do ONE of these two things. Not neither. Not "I'll write it up later".**

- **(a)** Confirm with the user, in the same turn as the proposed drop, that the feature is being dropped. Get an explicit yes.
- **(b)** Append an explicit entry to `docs/consolidation-plan.md` naming **which numbered slice** will carry the feature. "Later slices" / "future work" / "out of scope for now" without a number is not acceptable.

If the agent is unsure whether a given 0.4 feature counts as "present" (e.g. it existed but was broken, or was a dev-only debug screen), the default is (a) — ask. Erring toward asking is correct; this is a product charter, not just an architectural one.

## What counts as "collapsing a feature"

- Removing a UI affordance (button, pill, drawer, toggle, link) that exists in 0.4.
- Removing an endpoint / route (`?action=…`) that exists in 0.4, even a read-only one.
- Removing a display element (column, badge, meta line) from a card or list.
- Removing a configuration knob (settings toggle, env var, JSON key).

Renaming or refactoring something so it still works end-to-end is **not** collapsing. Deferring a feature explicitly, with a named slice, is also not collapsing — it's scoping.

## What the DoD ambiguity trap looks like

A slice's "definition of done" is written tightly, so a strict reading almost always permits trimming. In Slice 1:

> **Definition of done:** feed renders on both mothership and satellite; all card types look identical to 0.4 …

The strict reading is "only the cards need to be identical; everything around them is up for grabs". A plausible alternative reading is "the dashboard experience is identical minus writes". Both are defensible.

**When a DoD has more than one plausible reading and the agent picks the narrower one, that is a scope decision, not an engineering decision.** Scope decisions belong to the user. Surface the ambiguity; don't resolve it silently.

## Process for the agent

When starting a slice:

1. List every 0.4 feature in the area the slice touches (dashboard, Lex page, settings tab, etc.). File-level grep is enough; the list doesn't need to be exhaustive on the first pass.
2. For each feature, decide: **in this slice**, **deferred (name the slice)**, or **not applicable (0.4 bug / experiment / broken)**.
3. If any feature is deferred and the plan file doesn't already name a slice for it, add it to the plan before writing code. One line per item is enough.
4. If the decision is "not applicable", say so in the slice write-up in `README-REORG.md`.

## Enforcement

Reviewers (the user, future-me reading back, or any reviewer agent) should reject a slice whose commit message or `README-REORG.md` entry contains phrases like:

- "deliberately out of scope — they come back in later slices"
- "later slices"
- "future work"
- "will be addressed when needed"

unaccompanied by a numbered plan entry that can be grep'd for.

If the agent writes one of those phrases, the agent is required to stop and either (a) confirm or (b) update the plan, per the hard rule above.

## Pull-forwards (scope in the other direction)

**Silently landing work planned for Slice N+K inside Slice N is the same class of drift as deferrals** — the deliverable is bigger than the plan file promised, and readers grep'ing "PluginRegistry" or "HTTP client" will look at the wrong slice unless we name it.

**Hard rule:** If the agent implements something that `docs/consolidation-plan.md` currently attributes to a **later** numbered slice (infra, route, repository contract), the agent must **append or edit the plan in the same change** so the item is explicitly listed under the slice that actually shipped it (or add a "Pull-forward from Slice N" note under the later slice). Same bar as deferrals: **"we already did X in Slice N"** must be grep-able.

**README-REORG.md** should mention the pull-forward in the slice entry (one sentence: what landed early and why).
